The paper analyzes the knowledge base of the journal Cognitive Science, which is a multidisciplinary field that includes computer science, psychology, linguistics, philosophy, and neuroscience. The paper focuses on the changing disciplinary composition of the journal over three decades, which suggests that it may be relevant to several arXiv CS sub-categories. The paper's emphasis on analyzing referencing patterns and using factor analysis suggests that it may be most relevant to cs.DL (Digital Libraries) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). The paper's focus on interdisciplinary research and the integration of different fields suggests that it may also be relevant to cs.CL (Computation and Language), cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), and cs.CY (Computers and Society).
